Hi @AviHafner!

## Image

There is an image parser built into tablesorter (only in my fork), where you set the column header class with "sorter-image". By default, the parser extracts out the `alt` attribute content for sorting. If there is no `alt` attribute, then it falls back to the table cell text. You can change the targeted attribute by setting the [`imgAttr` option](http://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#imgattr).

This example uses the [`headers` option](http://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#headers) to set the parser:

```js
$(function(){
  $('table').tablesorter({
    // parse image title (value to be used while sorting & filtering)
    imgAttr : 'title',
    headers : {
      // this parser is auto-detected, but will only work if there is an
      // image in the cell in the first row
      0 : { sorter: 'image' }
    }
  });
});
```

## Link

If you want to sort by an `href`, then you'll need to set the [`textExtraction` option](http://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#textextraction) for that column to get the attribute from the link.

This example finds the `href` attribute from the first column (zero-based index):

```js
$(function(){
  $('table').tablesorter({
    textExtraction : {
      // the "url" parser is auto-detected so if your url starts with
      // "http", "https", "ftp" or "file" then it'll work
      0 : function(node, table, cellIndex) {
        return $(node).find('a').attr('href');
      }
    }
  });
});
```

If your url doesn't contain "http", "https", "ftp" or "file", then you can set the parser by adding "sorter-url" to the header, or setting the `headers` option.

