So I've double checked the behaviour of the javascript api and pyrebase is not following expected behaviour. 

If we have the following data:
```
0: {
  name: "john"
},
1: {
  name: "henry"
}
```
Here is the behaviour when using the official javascript library:
```
database.ref('test').child('people').once('value', function(snap) {
  snap.val() // [{name: "john"}, {name: "henry"}]
  snap.key // people
  snap.forEach(function(person) {
    person.val() // { name: "john" }
    person.key // 0
  });
});
```

And here is pyrebase's behaviour:
```
data = db.child('test').child('people').get()
data.val() # AttributeError: 'dict' object has no attribute 'key'
data.key() # people
for person in data.each():
    person.val() # AttributeError: 'dict' object has no attribute 'val'
    person.key() # AttributeError: 'dict' object has no attribute 'key'
```

So definitely some changes to make.

