I didn't quite catch this before, but `_burstColumn()`, `_adaptSegment()`, etc. were moved outside of the class itself.  I think it would have been better to make them static methods on the class, and for that matter, prefix with an additional `_` to take advantage of name mangling to better enforce scope of visibility. e.g.:

```
class TemporalMemory(object):
  ...
  @staticmethod
  def __burstColumn(...):
    ...
  
  def burstColumn(self):
    return self.__burstColumn()
```

@cogmission:
In the Proj.4 project that is the basis for pyproj I found in `geocent.c` the function `pj_Convert_Geodetic_To_Geocentric`. I simplified it according to epsg:3785 and ported it to Java.  Could you please check if this is what we are after and - if yes - whether my simplifications are correct? I'd hate implementing it into nupic if it is off the mark.

    /**
     * Returns geocentric coordinates converted from Long/Lat/Alt
     * 
     * @param lon	the longitude
     * @param lat	the lattitude
     * @param alt      the altitude in m
     * @return
     */
    protected double[] toGeocentric(double lon, double lat, double alt) {

        lon *= Math.PI / 180;
        lat *= Math.PI / 180;

        double PI_OVER_2 = Math.PI / 2;
	
        if (lat < -PI_OVER_2 && lat > -1.001 * PI_OVER_2 ) {
            lat = -PI_OVER_2;
        } else if ( lat > PI_OVER_2 && lat < 1.001 * PI_OVER_2 ) {
            lat = PI_OVER_2;
        } else if (lat < -PI_OVER_2 || lat > PI_OVER_2) { 
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("latitude out of range");
        }

        if (lon > Math.PI) {
            lon -= (2 * Math.PI);
        }
    
        double Rn = 6378137;
    
        double x = (Rn + alt) * Math.cos(lat) * Math.cos(lon);
        double y = (Rn + alt) * Math.cos(lat) * Math.sin(lon);
        double z = (Rn + alt) * Math.sin(lat);
   
        return new double[] { x, y, z };
    }

